article.headline: Georgetown 82, Cincinnati 67
article.story: WASHINGTON (AP) -- Roy Hibbert towered over his defenders to score a career-high 26 points on 11-for-13 shooting, leading Georgetown to an 82-67 victory over Cincinnati on Saturday for the Hoyas' fourth straight win. In a matchup that hardly seemed fair, the 7-foot-2 Hibbert stood 6 inches taller than any Bearcats starter, an advantage he exploited to push his Big East-leading field goal percentage above 70 percent for the season. Hibbert also grabbed 11 rebounds, blocked two shots and drew the foul that put Cincinnati's top scoring threat, Marcus Sikes, out of the game with more than 13 minutes remaining. Jeff Green added 17 points for the Hoyas (15-5, 5-2 Big East), who committed only five turnovers. Georgetown never trailed, but Cincinnati kept the game competitive with 3-point shooting, making 14 of 24 shots beyond the arc. Sikes made all five of his 3-point attempts and finished with 19 points, but he picked up his fourth and fifth fouls in a 13-second span and was gone with 13:19 to play. Deonta Vaughn added 18 points, and Marvin Gentry had 15 points for the Bearcats (10-10, 1-5), who have lost seven of eight and were seeking their first road conference win. Whether by tip-in, lay-in or short hook shot, Hibbert scored eight of Georgetown's first 11 field goals to start the second half. His inside basket with 6:22 to play gave the Hoyas a 66-54 lead, capping a 13-6 run. Gentry responded with another 3-pointer, but a dunk by Green 1 1/2 minutes later restored the double-digit lead for the rest of the game. Sikes scored 14 of Cincinnati's first 16 points to start the game, including a 3-pointer that banked in. Hibbert was Georgetown's early force with eight quick points, then he sat on the bench for 10 minutes while Green and Patrick Ewing Jr. led a spurt that built a 17-point lead. A minute later, freshman DaJuan Summers hurdled the first row of courtside seats to save the ball to Green, who fed Jessie Sapp for a dunk to make it 40-24 with 2:47 remaining. But Georgetown didn't score again in the half. Gentry scored eight points in an 11-0 run, pulling the Bearcats within 40-35 at the break. Hibbert took control again at the start of the second half, making three inside baskets in an 8-0 run to give the Hoyas a 13-point lead. The Bearcats needed more than three minutes to hit the rim at the start of the half- they committed three turnovers, and Gentry had a layup blocked by Hibbert.
